{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/564"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.13,0.08,0.05,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1053"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42100"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of worsening dyspnoea. His medical history includes untreated hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, and gout. He takes no regular medications. He is a smoker with a 50-pack-year history and drinks four to five standard drinks of alcohol a day on most days of the week. On examination, he is overweight and has crackles in both lung bases. His heart sounds are dual with an added S3 heart sound. His jugular venous pressure is 4 cm with a prominent a wave. Diuresis is commenced with furosemide tablets and fluid restrictions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management approach in addition to diuresis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perindopril","Atenolol","Isosorbide mononitrate","Verapamil","Bisoprolol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of heart failure, including dyspnoea, bibasal crackles, elevated jugular venous pressure, and an S3 gallop. The background of untreated hypertension and cardiovascular risk factors suggests heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend that all four classes of disease-modifying therapy\u2014renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi), heart failure\u2013specific beta-blockers, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists (MRA), and sodium-glucose cotransporter two inhibitors (SGLT2i)\u2014should be started at or soon after diagnosis of HFrEF, ideally within two to four weeks, unless contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEI) and is representative of the class of renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi), which also includes angiotensin receptor blockers and angiotensin receptor-neprilysin inhibitors. These agents reduce mortality and hospitalisation and also provide blood pressure control. While angiotensin receptor-neprilysin inhibitors have shown superior outcomes to ACEI in some studies, they are not currently funded for first-line use in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is a beta blocker, but it is not one of the heart failure\u2013specific beta-blockers with a proven mortality benefit in HFrEF. Additionally, beta-blockers should only be started after or alongside a RASi and when the patient is not congested. Initiating beta blockers in the setting of ongoing fluid overload can worsen symptoms and outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a heart failure\u2013specific beta blocker with proven benefits in HFrEF; however, as mentioned above, it should only be initiated after or alongside a RASi and when the patient is not experiencing congestion. Other heart failure\u2013specific beta blockers are carvedilol, nebivolol, and metoprolol succinate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsosorbide mononitrate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for angina and symptom relief in some cases of heart failure, but does not provide mortality benefit and is not indicated as initial therapy in the absence of angina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker that can worsen HFrEF due to its negative inotropic effects and should be avoided in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComprehensive management should also address modifiable risk factors such as smoking, alcohol intake, and weight, and include regular monitoring of renal function and electrolytes after starting a RASi.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initiation of all four classes of disease-modifying therapy is recommended within two to four weeks of diagnosis of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), unless contraindicated.","Renin-angiotensin system inhibitors (RASi) are a key first-line therapy in HFrEF.","Beta blockers should be started after or alongside a RASi, but only when the patient is not congested."],"references":["Atherton JJ, Audehm R, Connell C. Heart failure guidelines A concise summary for the GP. MedicineToday. 2019;20(6):14-24. Available at: https://medicinetoday.com.au/mt/2019/june/feature-article/heart-failure-guidelines-concise-summary-gp","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF). In: Therapeutic Guidelines: Cardiovascular [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 [cited 2025 Jun 3]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/","NPS MedicineWise [Internet]. 2021 [cited 2025 Jun 3]. Up-titrating heart failure medicines: A practical guide. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/news/up-titrating-heart-failure-medicines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-03T21:45:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-03T21:46:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104719"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA